<chapter xml:id="ch-summary-guide" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Summary Guide</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This is a non-comprehensive summary guide about the tools used.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-summary-descriptive">
    <title>Descriptive statistics</title>

    <table>
      <title/>
      <tabular halign="left">
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>Meaning</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-mean" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Average <mdash/> the "centre of gravity" of the data</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-sd" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>How clustered is the data around the mean (smaller figure means more clustered, larger figure closer to interquartile range means more spread out)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Skewness (see <xref ref="sec-skewnesskurtosis" text="title"/>)</cell>
          <cell>The asymmetry of the data compared to a normal distribution (bell curve)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Kurtosis (see <xref ref="sec-skewnesskurtosis" text="title"/>)</cell>
          <cell>Pointiness of the data. Smaller figure means more pointy, larger figure means less pointy</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-range" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>The spread of the data set between the maximum and minimum values</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Maximum (see <xref ref="sec-range" text="title"/>)</cell>
          <cell>The highest value in the data set</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Upper quartile (see <xref ref="sec-IQR" text="title"/>)</cell>
          <cell>25% of the data points reside at and above this value</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-median" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>This is the value of the data point in the middle (or the average of the two middle points in case of even number of data points). 50-50% of data points reside at above and below this value</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Lower quartile (see <xref ref="sec-IQR" text="title"/>)</cell>
          <cell>25% of the data points reside at and below this value</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Minimum (see <xref ref="sec-range" text="title"/>)</cell>
          <cell>The lowest value in the data set</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-summary-differences">
    <title>Analysing differences with hypothesis testing</title>

    <table>
      <title/>
      <tabular halign="left">
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
          <cell>Test</cell>
          <cell>Description</cell>
          <cell>Example from the chapter</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>CATEGORICAL DATA</em></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-goftest" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the observed data fits a theoretical distribution</cell>
          <cell>Probability of card suits being random</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-chisqindependence" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether two distributions are the same</cell>
          <cell>Probability that a member of species <m>j</m> gives response <m>i</m> to aliens</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-fisherexacttest" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether two distributions are the same (small sample sizes and contingency tables</cell>
          <cell>Witches' happiness being burned in Salem</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-mcnemar" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>2 by 2 contingency table with nominal data</cell>
          <cell>Whether the frequencies of suit choices are different the second time than the first time</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>NON-CATEGORICAL DATA</em></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>One group in one situation</em></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-ztest" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the mean is equal to a given hypothetical value (you know the population standard deviation and your sample size is large)</cell>
          <cell>The mean of grades in Dr Zeppo's class is above 67.5</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-onesamplettest" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the mean is equal to a given hypothetical value (you only have an estimated standard deviation, you cannot speak for the population)</cell>
          <cell>The mean of grades in Dr Zeppo's class is above 67.5</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>Two groups in one situation</em></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-studentttest" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Comparing two groups: Tests whether the means of two independent samples are equal (assumes normal distribution)</cell>
          <cell>The mean of grades of students tutored by Anastasia and Bernadette in Dr Harpo's class</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-welchttest" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Comparing two groups: Tests whether the means of two independent samples are equal (assumes unequal variances)</cell>
          <cell>The mean of grades of students tutored by Anastasia and Bernadette in Dr Harpo's class (with an alternative data set that violates normality assumption)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="subsec-mannwhitney" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the means of two independent samples are equal (assumes non-normal distribution)</cell>
          <cell>AFL games attendance if the game is finals or not</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>One group in two situations</em></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-pairedsamplesttest" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the means of two samples are equal (assumes normal distribution)</cell>
          <cell>Changes to the mean of grades between the first test and the second test in Dr Chico's class</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="subsec-wilcoxon" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the means of two paired samples are equal (assumes non-normal distribution)</cell>
          <cell>Whether a biology class has any effect on the happiness of students</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><em>Three or more groups</em></cell>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="ch-anova" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the means of three or more independent samples are equal (assumes normal distribution)</cell>
          <cell>Effects of 3 drugs on mood in our clinical trial</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="sec-kruskalwallis" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the means of three or more independent samples are equal (assumes non-normal distribution)</cell>
          <cell>Effects of 3 drugs on mood in our clinical trial (adjusted data set)</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><xref ref="ch-factorial-anova" text="title"/></cell>
          <cell>Tests whether the means of three or more independent samples are equal but with more than one grouping variable</cell>
          <cell>Effects of 3 drugs and 2 therapy methods on mood in our clinical trial</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

  </section>

